PY  - 2014
AB  - Within the context of the Lower Mekong Basin (LMB), irrigation is widely accepted uncritically as a public good that has positive benefits on both poverty reduction and food security. This brings to mind, Berkoff’s (2002) sardonic remark: “Irrigation is so obviously a good thing ‐ who can be against it?” While Overseas Development Aid (ODA) from Western nations supporting irrigation development was a prevalent feature of rural development programmes in Thailand in the 1960 ‐ 90s period, it has now been replaced in that country by domestically-sourced budgets, which continue to drive forward new system developments, constantly searching for new (or recycling old) sites and water resources to exploit, even if it means importing water from transboundary sources or overallocating water supplies. In the other countries of the LMB, Western ODA is still significant and increasingly is placed within a new justifying development narrative of a “water, energy and food nexus”, alongside climate change and food/water security concerns. However, there is strong evidence to suggest that a/ irrigation has not been as beneficial to vulnerable groups or the environment as is often assumed; and b/ the older lessons of irrigation development and management in Thailand are not being applied to or assimilated within the neighbouring states. Furthermore, there appears to be an over-emphasis by those concerned with the impacts of the present hydropower construction boom on the potential risks to food security and livelihoods, that tends to overlook similar or more serious development externalities from the irrigation sector. This paper raises some of these issues and highlights some pertinent questions for water resources planners, policy makers, development practitioners and researchers to consider.
