TI  - Do cooperatives help the poor? Evidence from Ethiopia
PY  - NA
AB  - This paper analyzes how producer cooperatives may bene t households in rural environments. In a multi-period model I characterize the conditions that must hold so that the always poor can exit poverty when participating in cooperatives. In particular, I explore whether cooperatives help poor households to exit poverty by increasing productivity and facilitating access to modern technologies that involve xed investments (soil conservation practices and irrigation systems). I test the implications of the model using the Ethiopian Rural Household Surveys (ERHS). Results indicate that cooperatives increased productivity for households that were not poor in 1994. Furthermore, while they had a negative e ect on adoption of xed cost technologies, the had a positive e ect on adoption of pesticides and participation in agricultural extension programs. Very preliminary, all comments welcome ∗I am extremely grateful to Professors Brad Barham and Laura Schechter for their advice and guidance, and to Professor Jennifer Alix-Garcia and the participants at various research meetings at the UW-Madison AAE Department for their helpful suggestions. I also thank Professor Camilo Garcia-Jimeno and Rebecca Cleary for their help at di erent stages of the project. I also gratefully acknowledge the nancial support of the AAE Department and the Penn Scholarship Fund at UW-Madison. Finally, I would like to thank Professors Jeremy Foltz and Belay Simane, the sta from Bacho Weliso Farmers Cooperative Union, Fanaye Tadesse, Gashaw Tadesse, Sileshi Bogale and Jemal Mahmud for their crucial support during eldwork. The data used in this paper have been made available by the Economics Department, Addis Ababa University, the Center for the Study of African Economies, University of Oxford and the International Food Policy Research Institute. Funding for data collection was provided by the Economic and Social Research Council (ESRC), the Swedish International Development Agency (SIDA) and the Uni